\begin{abstract}
Electrons excited after photon absorption in the photoemission process spend a finite time in the local atomic potential well before being photoemitted, as suggested by recent attosecond time-resolved photoemission experiments. According to the Eisenbud-Wigner-Smith model, the time-delay is due to a phase-shift of different transitions that occur in the process. Such a phase-shift is also at the origin of the angular dependent spin polarization of the photoelectron beam, observable in spin degenerate systems without angular momentum transfer by the incident photon. We propose a semi-quantitative model which permits to relate spin and time scales in photoemission from condensed matter targets. We also present the first experimental determination by spin- and angle-resolved photoemission spectroscopy (SARPES) of a finite inferior limit for the interaction time of photoelectrons. The inferior limit is found to be $62~as$ for electrons emitted from the \textit{sp}-bulk band of Cu(111).
\end{abstract}
\maketitle

Photoemission has been at the core of condensed matter physics studies for more than one century, both as a basic physical process and as platform for spectroscopic techniques. In the highly successful \emph{one-step model} the process is described as a quantum transition between initial and final state \cite{Damascelli:2004}.
Whereas enormous advances in the understanding of the energetics of the process have been achieved, the time scale of the photon absorption and electron emission has been typically neglected, with the common assumption of instantaneous excitation and emission of the electron. Only recently the first measurements of time-delays between electrons photoemitted from different bands have been performed \cite{Cavalieri:2007, Eckle:2008, Pazourek:2013, Lucchini:2015}, giving results in the attosecond domain that are still under active discussion \cite{Zhang:2011t}.

A complete description of the photoemission process in condensed matter must include the combination of all relevant transitions occurring after the photon absorption. The complex matrix elements describing each transition have a different phase, and their quantum interference determines the net total phase-shift~$\phi$ of the photoelectron wavefunction. The accumulated phase-shift corresponds to a time-delay for the emission of the photoelectron after photon absorption \cite{Heinzmann:2012}.
For simplicity we consider two generic transitions, $T_1$ and $T_2$, with a respective phase-shift $\phi$, as pictured in Fig.~\ref{fig:picture}(a). The relationship between $\phi$ and the time-delay $\tau_{\textsc{ews}}$ is obtained from the Eisenbud-Wigner-Smith (EWS) model \cite{Wigner:1955, Smith:1960}:

