	\centering
		\includegraphics[width=0.95\textwidth]{fig2.pdf}
	\caption{(a) $h\nu$ dispersion for $E_b$ close to the Fermi level, with the non-dispersive surface state and the \textit{sp}-bulk band; (b) bandmap at $h\nu=130~eV$ with the \textit{sp} state. Solid lines indicate the $E_b$ where the spin-resolved MDCs have been measured. The actual set of measurements was performed in a random sequence in order to prevent any time-related artifact; (c) $3$D spin resolved MDC along $x$ measured $0.2~eV$ below the Fermi level with $\pi$ polarized radiation and $h\nu=130~eV$. The total intensity and the three polarization components along $x$,$y$,$z$ are shown (circles) with a two vectors fit (solid lines); (d) Dependence on $E_b$ of the projection of $\textbf{P}$ along $y$ for the first of the two opposite polarization vectors from the fit; (e) measurement repeated for different $h\nu$, with estimated error bars shown for one data point.}
	\label{fig:data}
\end{figure*}
Our SARPES experiments were performed at the COPHEE endstation \cite{Hoesch:2002,Meier:2009NJP}. In Fig.~\ref{fig:picture}(b) a sketch of the experimental setup is shown. In this setup, the spin polarization component $\textbf{P}\cdot\hat{\textbf{n}}$ corresponds to $P_y$.
We measured the spin polarization of the \textit{sp}-bulk valence band of Cu(111) at different $E_b$. The sample was aligned with the $\Gamma K$ direction along $k_x$. The sample quality and cleanness were checked by measuring $E_b\approx440~meV$ for the surface state \cite{Reinert:2001}. Under these conditions the surface state shows only a Rashba-type spin splitting \cite{SOM} without spin interference effects \cite{Dil:2015}.

In order to maximize the counts of the spin-resolved measurements and to find a $h\nu$ where $r\approx 1$, optimal photon energies have been chosen after a $h\nu$ scan, shown in Fig.~\ref{fig:data}(a). Local maxima in intensity were found at $46~eV$ and $130~eV$, corresponding to two different Brillouin zones. A bandmap for $h\nu=130~eV$ is shown in Fig.~\ref{fig:data}(b). The band under consideration displays a nearly-free electron-like disperison with well defined symmetry and without any hybridization in a $2~eV$ range from the Fermi level.

In Fig.~\ref{fig:data}(c) the spin-resolved MDC measured $0.2~eV$ below the Fermi level is shown. Because the \textit{sp}-bulk band of Cu(111) is not spin-polarized in the initial state the clear measured spin polarization along each spatial component is generated during the photoemission process. We can exclude surface-induced Rashba-like effects \cite{Kimura:2010, Wissing:2013} as the only cause for the observed spin polarization because heavier Au(111) shows a polarization with similar magnitude \cite{SOM}. The spin polarization changes sign when crossing the peak maximum, thus resulting in a signal with two peaks. In order to determine the two spin polarization vectors in the $3D$ real space, a fitting routine was applied at the same time on the three polarization curves and the spin-integrated total intensity \cite{Meier:2009NJP, Meier:2008}, with Fig.~\ref{fig:data}(c) showing a best fit (solid lines). The two vectors are pointing in the opposite direction within the error margin of $\pm 5^\circ$ for each component. This occurs in every dataset and for simplicity we will consider from here on only the vector at lower momentum $k_x$. A best fit is obtained for all our datasets with $\left|\textbf{P}\right|=1$. This is related to the fact that the spin detection occurs in the far-field of the photoemission process \cite{Park:2012L}. The only change of the spin polarization vector $\textbf{P}$ will thus be a rotation in space.

As mentioned above, for the $\phi$ related effects we are interested in the $P_y$ component. In particular, by repeating the fitting procedure for the measurements at different $E_b$ a plot of $P_y(E_b)$ was constructed, as shown in Fig.~\ref{fig:data}(d). Without considering the point at $E_F$ which will be discussed later, the trend is a linear dependence of $P_y$ on $E_b$, with a slope of $-0.13\pm0.01~eV^{-1}$.
By using eq.~\eqref{eq:result} we can estimate $\tau_{\textsc{ews}}>62~as$, a finite inferior limit for the EWS time-delay occurring in the photoemission of electrons from the \textit{sp}-bulk band of Cu(111). The linear dependence of $P_y(E_b)$ shows that the time-delay is a constant for the electrons from the \textit{sp}-band in this $2~eV$ window, which also means that $\phi$ linearly varies with $E_b$.

The $P_y(E_b)$ measurement has been repeated for various photon energies as shown in Fig.~\ref{fig:data}(e). The measurement at $h\nu=130~eV$ has been repeated twice in order to check the robustness of the measurement. At $h\nu=127~eV$, even though the polarization signal is comparable to the previous case \cite{SOM}, it does not clearly vary with $E_b$. With less favorable conditions for the matrix elements we cannot conclude anything about $\tau_{\textsc{ews}}$. At $h\nu=46~eV$ we observe another favorable combination, where the slope of $P_y(E_b)$ is $+0.12~eV^{-1}$, similar to what was obtained for $h\nu=130~eV$, but with inverted sign. This is most likely related to the crossing of an odd number of Cooper minima from $46~eV$ to $130~eV$, resulting in a switch of the sign of the radial part of the initial state wavefunction \cite{Fano:1968}, reflected in the sign of the phase in the two measurements. The other two components of the spin polarization $P_x$ and $P_z$ \cite{SOM}, not related to $\phi$ for symmetry considerations \cite{SOM}, might help to develop a model for~$\eta$.

\begin{figure} [ht]
	\centering
		\includegraphics[width=0.48\textwidth]{fig3.pdf}
	\caption{(a) Spin polarization component $P_y$ of a bandmap constructed from experimental  for MDCs along $k_x$ measured with $\pi$ polarized $h\nu=130~eV$; (b) KKR calculation performed for the very same experimental parameters.}
	\label{fig:comparison}
\end{figure}
In Fig.~\ref{fig:comparison}(a) a summary for the $P_y$ component from all the MDCs performed with $h\nu=130~eV$ is shown. It is clear how the $sp$-band is made of a two-peaks spin signal, as already mentioned. This effect is a sign that the measured spin polarization is related to photoemission process interference effects, since one single band is measured without spin resolution as well established in literature \cite{Courths:1984} and shown in Fig.~\ref{fig:data}(b). In order to understand this critical feature, fully relativistic self consistent multiple-scattering or Korringa-Kohn-Rostoker (KKR) calculations have been performed \cite{Ebert:2011}. In Fig.~\ref{fig:comparison}(b) results of ARPES calculations for a semi-infinite system in the framework of the fully relativistic one-step model of photoemission \cite{Braun:1996,Minar:2011} within its spin-density matrix formulation \cite{Braun:2014} are shown. Also in this case the \textit{sp}-band gives rise to two spin signals matching closely to the experimental results, thus excluding any possible artifact in the measurement. Note that this double feature has already been observed, but not discussed, in previous calculations \cite{Winkelmann:2012}. The main qualitative difference between theory and experiments consists in the actual values of $P_y$ for the two features. However, this does not affect the resulting $\tau_{\textsc{ews}}$. A refining of parameters in the calculations could improve the already good match. Also, the spurious spin effects modeled with $\eta$ in eq.~\eqref{eq:model} might contribute with a background spin signal in $P_y$.\\



It is important to underline the nature of the measured time-delay since the chronoscopy of photoemission is a fundamental topic in modern physics \cite{Pazourek:2015}. In order to picture this time scale, we suggest to naively divide the one-step photoemission model into three time steps: light absorption, atomic electron excitation, and photoelectron emission. At present, it is difficult to tell which of these steps occur in a finite time. There might exist a time-threshold for light absorption, since $86~as$ correspond to less than $3$ cycles of a light wave of $130~eV$. Then it might take a finite time to perform the electronic transition, which corresponds to a decoherence time required by the ground state wavefunction to collapse \cite{Schlosshauer:2005}. Lastly, the electron excited above the vacuum level spends a finite time before escaping the atomic environment because of the interaction with the nucleus and the electron cloud. The third step is what is considered in the half-scattering picture, but also the other two might play a role in the measured time-delay between the photon absorption and the subsequent electron emission. Experiments with ultrashort pulses on a system with sufficiently long $\tau_{\textsc{ews}}$ would test the first step.

In attosecond-resolved ARPES the relative time-delay is between the photoelectrons emitted by different bands \cite{Cavalieri:2007, Eckle:2008, Pazourek:2013, Lucchini:2015}. At present, an absolute determination of the time scale related to a single band can only be indirectly obtained by comparison with calculations: in a recent work on Cu(111) \cite{Lucchini:2015} a delay of $50~as$ is reported, similar to our measurement.
Whereas time-resolved spectroscopy gives a \textit{relative} measure between two bands $\Delta\tau_{\textsc{ews}}$, the rotation of the spin polarization with $E_b$ works as an ``internal clock'' for the \emph{absolute} interaction time of the photoemission process $\tau_{\textsc{ews}}$. In fact in our model the phase-shift is between the interfering paths that build up the \emph{same} photoelectron final state. At the origin of the interfering different transitions there could be a continuous interband coupling mechanism, equivalent for solids of the interchannel coupling in photoionization which leads to a finite attosecond time scale \cite{Pabst:2011}.
To this extent, the two techniques can be considered as complementary. It is important also to underline that the semi-quantitative model presented here permits to extract the time information from non-time-resolved calculations, which would be very powerful when performed on systems that are experimentally difficult to probe with time-resolved or spin-resolved ARPES.

Finally we want to discuss the measurement performed at the Fermi level (see Fig.~\ref{fig:data}(d)) which is peculiar since it clearly deviates from the linear trend of $P_y(E_b)$. Because correlation effects become evident typically in a narrow energy window close to $E_F$

, and given the connection of the photoemission phase-shifts with the quasi-particle self-energy \cite{Fishbane:1969}, we speculate that such a deviation is related to these phenomena. A link between correlations and phase-shift probed via the spin polarization would open a whole new range of studies employing SARPES as a technique for the definition of the self-energy time- and spin-structure and would bring qualitatively new valuable information for the understandings of strongly correlated materials.\\

